'''Ahistoricism''' refers to a lack of concern related to history, historical development, or tradition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/ahistoricism|title=ahistoricism|publisher=Mirriam-Webster Dictionary Online|accessdate=2008-11-27}}</ref>
Ahistoricism is most frequently used as a criticism, referring to being historically inaccurate or ignorant (for example, an ''ahistorical'' attitude). It can also describe a person's failure to frame an argument or issue in a historical context or to disregard historical fact or implication.<ref>{{cite book|last=Pepper|first=David|title=Eco-socialism: From Deep Ecology to Social Justice|publisher=Routledge|date=1993|pages=143-144|isbn=0415097193, 9780415097192}}</ref>. Further, it can describe a view that history is unimportant or has no relevance to modern life or decision-making.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defineonline.com/Definition.aspx?Word=ahistoricism|title=ahistoricism|publisher=Define Online|accessdate=2008-11-27}}</ref>
